external_knowledge:
- "Epicenter of the storm" refers to the county with the highest average test positivity rate;
- The test positivity rate is the percentage of tests that come back positive for COVID-19;
- The '%' sign is removed from the `test_positivity_rate` column before conversion to a real number.

- "Highest vaccination rate" means the county with the greatest percentage of the population vaccinated;
- "Above-average COVID-19 cases" means the county has more confirmed cases than the average number of cases across all counties;
- "Above-average data access frequency" means the county's data is accessed more often than the average access frequency of all data entries.

sql:
SELECT MAX(total_cases) AS max_total_cases
FROM (
    SELECT county_name, SUM(covid_count) AS total_cases
    FROM covid_data
    GROUP BY county_name
);

SELECT county_name 
FROM covid_data 
WHERE CAST(REPLACE(vaccination_rate, '%', '') AS REAL) = (
  SELECT MAX(CAST(REPLACE(vaccination_rate, '%', '') AS REAL)) 
  FROM covid_data
);

SELECT MAX(total_capacity) AS highest_capacity
FROM (
  SELECT SUM(hospital_capacity) AS total_capacity
  FROM covid_data
  GROUP BY location_id
);

SELECT county_name, covid_count
FROM covid_data
WHERE covid_count = (SELECT MAX(covid_count) FROM covid_data);

external_knowledge:
- 'latest' refers to the most recent data entry for each county based on the date;
- 'users with specific roles' are those whose roles match the county names, which is an unusual condition and may require further clarification;
- 'more than 100 total cases' means the sum of confirmed cases for each county is greater than 100.

- "Highest number of confirmed cases" refers to the top 5 counties by total COVID-19 cases;
- "Hospital and ICU capacities" are the maximum values reported for each county;
- "Average test positivity rate" is the mean of the test positivity rates across all data points for each county.

- "confirmed COVID-19 cases" refers to the number of people who have tested positive for the virus;
- "vaccination rate" is the percentage of the population that has received at least one dose of a COVID-19 vaccine;
- "multiple data entries" implies that the county has been recorded more than once in the dataset.

- "highest total COVID-19 cases" refers to counties with more than 1000 confirmed cases;
- "user access patterns" include users who have accessed the data more than 10 times;
- "hospital and ICU capacities" are averaged across the data entries for each county;
- "vaccination rates" and "test positivity rates" are also averaged and converted from percentage strings to numerical values.

- "more than a thousand confirmed cases" refers to `total_covid_cases > 1000`;
- "frequently and recently accessed" refers to `total_access_count > 5` and `recent_access_date >= '2022-01-01'`;
- "since the dawn of 2022" refers to the date range starting from January 1, 2022.

- Vaccination rate categories are defined as 'Low' (less than 50%), 'Moderate' (50% to 69%), and 'High' (70% and above);
- The new case rate is calculated as the number of new cases divided by the population;
- The cumulative new cases and hospital capacity are calculated over the same vaccination rate category.

- "significant number of COVID-19 cases and deaths" refers to more than 10,000 cases and 500 deaths;
- "sufficient hospital and ICU capacities" refers to an average hospital capacity greater than 50 and an average ICU capacity greater than 10;
- "large population" refers to a population greater than 1,000,000;
- "substantial land area" refers to a land area greater than 10,000 square units;
- "high level of data access activity" refers to more than 100 access events and a total access duration greater than 3,600 seconds (1 hour).

- "vaccination rate surpasses the halfway mark" refers to a vaccination rate greater than 50%;
- "ICU beds are more than half available" means the ICU capacity is greater than 50%;
- "average count of new and recovered cases" refers to the average number of new cases and recovered cases over the selected period.

- "highest peak" refers to the county with the highest average test positivity rate;
- "average test positivity rate" is calculated by averaging the test positivity rates for each county;
- "test positivity rate" is the percentage of positive tests out of all tests conducted.

sql:
SELECT county_name, SUM(covid_test) AS total_tests
FROM covid_data
GROUP BY county_name;
